Detailed Description

A Stored Bookmark Managed Object.

May be a Collection, Folder, Bookmark or Separator

Member Function Documentation

- (void) addTags: (id)  additionalTags  

Adds additional tags to the receivers tags set.

Note that we store 'tags' as a simple attribute, an array of NSStrings, and not a relationship. So we don't have the 'addTags:' accessor that would be provided by Core Data if 'tags' was a relationship.

Parameters:
additionalTags Either an NSArray* or NSSet* of strings, the new tags to be added

- (void) appendChildren: (NSArray*)  children  

Appends an ordered array of new children to the children of the receiver.

The index of the first element in the array is set to be one more than the highest existing index in the receiver's set of children, and then they increase from there.

Parameters:
children The children to be appended.

- (void) assembleAsTreeWithBar: (Stark*)  bar
menu: (Stark*)  menu
unfiled: (Stark*)  unfiled
ohared: (Stark*)  ohared 

Assuming receiver is the root of a tree, given optionally the four permanent hartainers, grafts them together properly and cleans everything up.

Finds immoveable branches either as arguments or already in receiver's children: If arguments bar, menu, unfiled or ohared are nil, will examine receiver's children for item with sharype = SharypeBar, SharypeMenu, SharypeUnfiled or SharypeOhared respectively.  If one of these hartainers is not found in either location, it will remain nil.  This nil is the expected result when the startainer being assembled does not support the hartainer(s).

After finding or not finding these four hartainer(s),

  1. Sets the name of each found hartainer.
  2. Sets the sharype of the receiver to SharypeRoot.
  3. Sets the sharypes of each found hartainer.
  4. Sets relationships so that each of the found hartainer(s) is a child of the receiver and the receiver is a parent of each found hartainer(s).
  5. Sets index(es) of each found hartainers to the standard order: bar first if it exists, then menu, then unfiled, then ohared. The indexes of the receiver's other children, presumably soft folders, are adjusted so that they begin after the hartainers.

This method is invoked at the end of readExternalNoPrereqs by Extore subclasses.  The relationship-setting step is needed because te ixternalizeFromStartainer::: methods need a known configuration for the source: Are the hartainers children of root, or are they not?  I believe that, in some subclasses, the readExternalNoPrereqs method places them as children of root, but others do not.  It might be nice to someday go through all of those subclasses, change if needed so that they do ^not^ place the hartainers into root, then eliminate that step, and finally modify ixternalizeFromStartainer::: methods so as to access the hartainers using -bar, -menu, -unfiled, and -oshared instead of iterating through root's children.

Parameters:
bar The bar of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.
menu The menu of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.
unfiled The unfiled of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.
shared The shared of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.

- (void) createFoldersFromTags: (NSNumber*)  createFoldersFromTags  

Folder-izes a Stark containing only one generation of children, by creating folders named after bookmarks' tags and moving the bookmarks into them.

Places each child in a new subfolder of the receiver, named after one of the receiver's tags. 

Parameters:
createFoldersFromTags The integer value of this number should be one of those enumerated in BkmxCreateFoldersFromTags. It specifies whether no folders should be created, one folder may be created, or multiple folders, each containing a copy of the tagged child should be created for children that have multiple tags.  If this value is BkmxCreateFoldersFromTagsNone, this method is a no-op.

- (void) moveToBkmxParent: (Stark*)  newParent
atIndex: (unsigned int)  newIndex 

Does the actions required to move a stark from one parent to another, or to delete it.

To add as last child, pass newIndex=NSNotFound. If index given would leave a gap between receiver and siblings, adds as last sibling instead.

To delete the receiver, pass newParent = nil .  This also removes from previous parent, and also deletes any descendants because in the data model for Starks the parent -> child relationship has Delete Rule = Cascade.

Logs an internal error if new parent's moc != receiver's moc.

Parameters:
newParent The new parent to which the receiver should be added as a child, or nil if the desired action is to delete the receiver.
newIndex The index (position) at which the receiver should be added

- (void) overwriteAttributesFromStark: (Stark*)  stark  

Invokes -overwriteAttributes:fromStark:, passing -allAttributes as the first argument.

This is similar to but not quite the same as the one-liner [self setValuesForKeysWithDictionary:[stark attributesDictionary]] ;.  You see, -[<NSKeyValueCoding> setValuesForKeysWithDictionary:] sets an NSNull for nil values.  This method actually sets those values to nil instead of an NSNull.  But I'm not sure if attributes can be nil.  So maybe I should use that method. See message from Ben Trumbull.

- (void) overwriteBrowprietaryValuesExceptForExformat: (NSString*)  exceptExformat
fromStark: (Stark*)  stark 

Overwrites in the reciever all browprietary values for all keys and all exformats, except those of a given exformat, from the browprietary values of a given stark.

If the given stark has browprietary values for some non-excepted exformat, and the receiver also has browprietary values for the same exformat, all key/value pairs for that exformat in the receiver's browprietary values will be overwritten.  If the receiver has one or more values for keys in an overwritten exformat that the given stark does not have, those key/value pairs will be removed.

Parameters:
exceptExformat The exformat for which the receiver's browprietaryValues will not be overridden, in case both the receiver and the given stark have browprietary values for this exformat
stark The stark from which browprietary values will be copied

- (void) overwriteExidsExceptForBrowid: (Browid*)  exceptBrowid
fromStark: (Stark*)  stark 

Overwrites in the receiver all exids from another stark, except the exid for a given browid.

Parameters:
exceptBrowid The browid for which the receiver's exid, will not be overridden, in case both the receiver and the given stark have exids for this browid
stark The stark from which exids will be copied

- (void) realizeIsExpandedIntoOutline: (NSOutlineView*)  outlineView  

Expands or collapses the representation of the receiver in a given outline view if its current expanded/collapsed state does not match the receiver's isExpanded property.

Seems like this would logically be in the outline view, but it needs to be a Stark method to be used recursively.

Supposedly, will post the will/did/expand/collapse notifications.  This is a waste of processor cycles because I use these notifications to set the isExpanded property.  In other words, it does the converse of what I just did, which is unnecessary.  However, when I sampled with Activity Monitor while expanding an outline of 50,000 items, this method did not have any notification postings, outlineViewItemDidExpand or outlineViewItemDidCollapse invocations under it.

Parameters:
outlineView The outline view in which the receiver's representation may be affected.

Parameters:

- (Stark *) replicatedOrphanStarkSameExids: (BOOL)  sameID
startainer: (NSObject <Startainer> *)  startainer 

Returns an new, inserted stark containing most of the receiver's current non-nil attributes as keys and values.

This method is used as a first step in making a copy of a Stark.  The new Stark returned will be inserted into the managed object context of the given startainer.

  Relationships are never copied, only attributes.  If sameExids is NO, the exids key is also omitted from the result .  A new exid may later be set, and a new parent.

In the name, the word "replica" is used instead of "copy", so as to not have a Cocoa memory management implication.

Parameters:
sameID If YES, and if the receiver has an object for key constKeyExids", that key/value pair appears in the result.  If NO, the constKeyExids key/value pair is always omitted.
startainer The startainer into whose managed object context the new stark should be inserted.
Returns:
An autoreleased NSDictionary replicating the attributes of the receiver as described.

- (Stark *) replicatedOrphanStarkSameExidsInStartainer: (NSObject <Startainer> *)  startainer  

Invokes replicatedOrphanStarkSameExids:startainer: with sameID = YES.

Provided as a convenience to simplify the signature of replicatedStarkInBookshelf:sameID: so that methods like performSelector: can be used to recursively invoke it without having to create a (gasp!) NSInvocation.

Parameters:
startainer The startainer into whose managed object context the new stark should be inserted.

Parameters:

- (void) setRssArticlesFromAndRemoveStarks: (NSArray*)  starks  

Converts an array of starks to an array of NSCoding-encodeable dictionaries, sets this array as the rssArticles of the receiver, and finally removes the given starks from the receiver's managed object context.

This method is necessary because, in parsing Firefox bookmarks, it is impossible to distinguish an rss article from a regular bookmark until you see that the parent is a live rss feed.  Therefore, it is easier to insert them as starks and then later use this method to get the array which is encoded as a simple attribute into the document's object graph.

The reverse of this method is -[ExternalizeOperations restoreRssArticlesInsertAsChildStarks].

Parameters:
starks The array of starks which will be converted, set and removed.

- (NSString *) toolTipForTableColumn: (NSTableColumn*)  tableColumn  

Returns a tool tip appropriate to a given table column.

The given table column is used to determine the relevant attribute to be expressed in the returned toolTip.

If the table column's identifier begins "userDefined" and tableColumn responds to -userDefinedAttribute, that attribute becomes the relevant attribute. Else, if the receiver responds to identifier as an attribute directly, that attribute becomes the relevant attribute. Else, returns nil.

Property Documentation

- (NSDictionary*) exids [read, write, retain]

A dictionary of the receiver's external store identifiers (exids).

Each key is a browid (browfile identifier).  Most starks, being read in from a single browfile, will have only one entry in this dictionary.

- (NSArray*) rssArticles [read, write, retain]

The receiver's rssArticles, as a transformed array of dictionaries containing the attributes of each rss article.

The setter is custom.

Setter customizations.  For each stark in the given array, the setter appends a dictionary to the receiver's rssArticles array, and finally deletes each stark in the given array from the receiver's managed object context.

- (NSString*) shortcut [read, write, retain]

A unique identifier string assigned by the user.

Different extores use different names for this attribute: Camino: Shortcut Firefox: Keyword Magnolia: Short Name OmniWeb: Keyword Opera: Nickname

- (NSArray*) tags [read, write, retain]

The receiver's tags, as set in Firefox, del.icio.us, etc.

tags must be unique. If you setTags: including duplicates, duplicates will be discarded. Reasons why tags is an array instead of a set: Transformerless binding to an NSTokenField Possibility that user(s) may expect tags order to be preserved At least one other reason which I forgot right now.

- (NSString*) url [read, write, copy]

The web site address of the receiver.  May be nil.

The getter is standard but a custom setter which sets the transient property urlNormalized to nil whenever url is changed.  This is because urlNormalized is derived directly from url but is cached as a transient property for efficiency.  Note that the getter may return nil.

- (NSString *) urlNormalized [read, retain]

Returns a version of the receiver's url, normalized so that slightly different urls which will visit the same resource have the same normalized url.

urlNormalized is derived from url. But this method runs ALOT when looking for duplicates. Therefore, for efficiency, we cache it in this transient property. Since it depends on url, it is set to nil and thus forced to be recalculated whenever url is changed. The private setter is only used to set to nil.
